💪🏻3 razones por las que no ganas fuerza💪🏻

✅Demasiadas demandas fisiológicas✅

Es normal disfrutar de la camaradería que brindan los bootcamps, pero seamos claros: el entrenamiento de fuerza no es un deporte de equipo, no dejes que tus amigos fofisanos te convenzan de lo contrario. Para los deportistas de alto nivel, es un medio para un fin, y para los competidores de fuerza y los levantadores serios, es un fin en sí mismo.

Participar regularmente en bootcamps, entrenamientos en circuito y similares puede cargarse tus ganancias de fuerza rápidamente.

🥃Bebes demasiado🍺

Todo bebedor sabe que tres copas acaban siendo seis, y un atracón a las 2 de la mañana parece una buena opción nutricional. Además el alcohol es poco amigo de tu composición corporal, ya que una vez consumido, se descompone en acetato y temporalmente se convierte en la principal fuente de combustible de tu cuerpo, dando lugar a que los CH no utilizados se almacenen en forma de grasa--uno de los motivos de las barriga cerveceras.

El alcohol además afecta negativamente al control motor, la fuerza, la potencia y la coordinación y consumirlo regularmente en grandes cantidades puede tener efectos a largo plazo sobre tus capacidades motoras. Además, el consumo excesivo puede aumentar la probabilidad de anafilaxia, asma y arritmias inducidas por el ejercicio, y dar lugar a una mala absorción de tiamina, vitamina B12, ácido fólico y zinc.

😴Duermes poco, o mal💤

La frase esa de "dormiré cuando esté muerto" tal vez te funcione si eres un broker, pero no si quieres ganar fuerza. El sueño es esencial para la salud y el rendimiento.

A medida que nuestro día llega a su fin, nuestros sistemas fisiológicos comienzan a ralentizarse. Cuando nos relajamos por la noche, aparece la somnolencia, nuestras ondas cerebrales se vuelven más sincrónicas, los músculos comienzan a relajarse y una vez avanza el sueño, los músculos se relajan por completo y entramos en períodos de sueño más profundo (REM) en los cuales la hormona del crecimiento y la testosterona se secretan en abundantes cantidades.

¡Intenta dormir un mínimo de 7-8 horas! Gracias a Joe Giadonato por su contribución y al modelo James Strickland

🧠Mental Conditioning Program🧠

🤜Mind power and successful mental conditioning come only with a sustained and sincere effort. You can’t make a wish and hope that it comes true and then forget about working on it.

👏The mind reacts much the same way the body does. If you train and condition it regularly, it will respond with a performance that you can always count on and be proud of.

🧘‍♂️Some of the key ingredients to an effective mind conditioning program are motivation, incentive, visualization, and, most important of all, belief.

⚔️2009 study published in The Perceptual Motor Skills Journal showed that when athletes believe in their competition training plans, they are more likely to be victorious in their given sport.

💀The power of belief may even be related to fatigue.

👆A 2009 study published in The European Journal of Applied Physiology entitled “The Limit to Exercise Tolerance in Humans: Mind over Muscle” challenged the notion that fatigue causes exhaustion and showed that exhaustion might be caused by perceived rate of effort.

💪What does this mean to you?

🙏It means you’ve got to believe.🙏

✅You’ve got to believe in yourself, in your talents and capabilities, in your goals and all you hope to achieve, and in your methods for achieving them.

💪The beginning of understanding what your mind holds in store for you is a simple realization. You must realize that within you is all the power you need to succeed both in training and dieting, which will ultimately lead to success in competition. Within you is all the potential for success. Within you is the brain power of a superman, or superwoman.

🍶Once you make this realization—that your mind holds a vast wealth of knowledge, information, control, power, ability, and potential—you can start to tap into that power. You can delve into your own secret depths and find out what you’re really made of.

BIG BENCH SECRETS: ISOMETRICS⁣
⁣
EDIT: When doing isometric bench presses, be sure the power rack is bolted down. Especially if you can bench the weight of the rack.😜⁣
⁣
⁣
When training most of us only train the beginning and the end of the movement, esp with accessories. I.e. tricep accessories, back accessories and chest accessories, neglecting the mid range (usually where a sticking point/ weak point in the lift can occur).⁣
⁣
Working with isometric presses, you can work that specific range of the lift, doing it with alot of time under tension that is usually lost during reps, and do it without moving the muscle at all! Another added benefit is the mind muscle connection. During normal training reps, it can be difficult to mentally connect with the muscle, usually relying on the body's automated response you have trained it to do and because they are usually completed alot faster. Isometric presses allow you to slow that down and focus on the muscle contraction therefore strengthening the connection between your mind and muscle.⁣
⁣
How to setup:⁣
Use a bench in a power rack, setup the safety pins so you and the bar are under them and the point where the bar touches the bottom of the immovable pins.  Place the bar so it touches the pins approximately one to two inches below your perceived sticking point during a normal rep. Only doing singles, resetting after each one. Hold each contraction for 6-10 seconds.  I typically do no more than three singles after all of my main bench sets once per week.⁣

Off season bench training with a wider grip.

The "ideal" arm position on the bench is to have the wrist stacked over the elbow joint. Now, this is not the end all. If you can develop a solid technique through a wider or narrower grip, then do what works. I have benched wider grip for the better part of my powerlifting career, as I found myself getting heavier (into the mid 600s) I found myself wanting to grip the bar closer and closer, because I got more power and was more stable that way. The key to a close grip bench is tremendous tricep strength as well as a the ability to generate alot of speed and power from the chest as to not get stuck half way up before the triceps can take over. An added benefit of close grip is it protects the pecs and shoulders from injury more than a wider grip since those areas aren't stressed as much under heavy loads and volume. BUT there is a limit, move in TOO close and the leverages and stability can be compromised, either because the weight gets too heavy and tou cannot generate the needed speed off the chest, or you can no longer maintain the stability needed (think of trying to balance a barbell on a narrow point). THIS limit is the main reason why I am changing my grip up. I dont feel I have yet plateaued with the previous close grip, but the best way to combat a plateau is to not have one at all. When moving 700 lbs I want the best foundation possible, by getting used to a wider grip I can always move in slightly as we get heavier and still be wider than I was previously and at the very least with wider grip training now my pecs, shoulders and back will have developed to help build a bigger base for not only a 700 lb bench, but beyond.

Did you know that the width of your grip can impact your bench press performance? Here's a breakdown of the pros and cons of each grip width to help you determine which grip is best for you!

👉 Wide Grip:
✅ Allows for greater activation of the pectoral muscles
✅ Shorter range of motion, which can allow you to lift more weight
❌ Puts more stress on your shoulders and may cause injury if not performed correctly
❌ Can be uncomfortable for some lifters if they lack the necessary shoulder mobility

👉 Narrow Grip:
✅ Places greater emphasis on the triceps, which can increase lockout strength
✅ Places less stress on the shoulders, reducing risk of injury
❌ Longer range of motion, which can make the lift more difficult
❌ Places less emphasis on the chest, which may not be suitable for bodybuilders or those looking to primarily train their pecs

"💪🏋️ The Bench Press Grip Dilemma: Narrow vs. Wide Grip 🏋️💪

Are you struggling to increase your weight and reps in the bench press? You might be doing it wrong! One of the most debated topics among lifters is the grip width. Should you take a wide grip or a narrow grip?

✅ Narrow Grip: Emphasizes the triceps more and reduces the stress on the shoulder joints. But beware of reduced chest activation, limited range of motion, and potential elbow discomfort.

✅ Wide Grip: Puts greater emphasis on the pectoral muscles, allows for better range of motion, and more chest activation. However, it could potentially stress your shoulder joints more, limit triceps activation, and lead to wrist pain.

So, which one is better? The answer depends on YOUR goals and body mechanics. Looking to target your chest muscles and build size? A wider grip may be for you. Looking to increase your overall strength and lift more weight? You might want to go narrower.

But remember, no matter the grip you choose, maintain proper form!! A proper grip is essential!
